textDisplay:
These jokes are incredibly offensive, but I love them, because they aren't "shooting down", they are satire, making fun of paedophilia, sexual assault, sexism, racism, the superficiality of Hollywood, the greed of capitalism. All of these are worthy targets. You cannot compare this to insulting a woman's baldness due a medical condition.
In a roundabout but very effective way, this is altruism. It is bringing the topics that are needing to be platformed to the public eye, and rightfully shaming the culture that propagates them.
The G.I. Jane joke was targeted at a woman's rightful insecurity. For anyone who is struggling to understand this: take a few seconds to imagine into losing your hair against your will as a Hollywood actress.
The point here isn't "never be offensive", it's be offensive in the right ways, to the right people (or ideas). And if you are shooting down, humiliating disability or illness, I am not sure we should condone that just as much as we shouldn't condone a slap, or we should at least understand why a slap isn't a completely unforeseen response.
Ricky's Judy Dench/James Cordon jokes were of a different sort, closer to or over that line.
Chris Rock may not have known about Jada's condition, and I love and respect the man, but this does not negate the discussion as Will wasn't aware of this, either.

In a roundabout but very effective way, this is altruism. It is bringing the topics that are needing to be platformed to the public eye, and rightfully shaming the culture that propagates them.
The G.I. Jane joke was targeted at a woman's rightful insecurity. For anyone who is struggling to understand this: take a few seconds to imagine into losing your hair against your will as a Hollywood actress.
The point here isn't "never be offensive", it's be offensive in the right ways, to the right people (or ideas). textDisplay:
How to Play the Game of Life
Why do children wake up with their eyes wide open and jump out of bed while we open them just wide enough to see the phone so we can set it to snooze? Why are young people energetic and ready to “conquer the world” while older people are cautious and hesitant? Can we stay young-spirited forever? After all, if life is not a game, there is no excitement in it. And if there is no excitement in life, what is the point of living?
If we want to keep enjoying, we need to make life a lifelong game. This game is very different from anything we know. It is not about what we can receive, but about what we can discover! By connecting to other people, we discover new worlds, other people’s worlds!
How do we achieve this? Quite simply, we need to focus on others rather than on ourselves. This may sound simple, but if you try it, you will realize how self-absorbed you are.
We are all like that. Even those who feel that they are generous and giving are absorbed in their giving and do not see how much they do it for their own interest, and how they are focused on their own benefit when they give. Giving is fine, but the focus is the point here. Had the focus been on the receiver, the giver would have discovered countless revelations that are hidden from a self-centered eye.
For the game to succeed, you need partners. It is impossible to play the game of giving without people to whom you can give and from whom you can receive. Therefore, there must be a group of people, up to ten or so, who play the game together.
In order to succeed in discovering the other players’ worlds, we need to think good thoughts about them. Otherwise, we will have no incentive to approach them, no desire to discover their world. We can think good thoughts about each other if we do good things for one another. These can be the simplest things, but they must make us feel good about each other. Positive thoughts about each other bring us closer, and closeness opens our minds and hearts to others, so we can see the world through their eyes.
As with any game, the more we practice, the better we get, and the harder, yet more rewarding the game becomes. But unlike any other game, as we improve in it, we will find that our entire perspective on life changes and expands, and we become wiser and more competent.
The game of life, unlike any other game, reveals to us the secrets of life, the secrets of reality, because when you can look at something from all angles, nothing remains hidden from you.

After all, if life is not a game, there is no excitement in it. And if there is no excitement in life, what is the point of living?
If we want to keep enjoying, we need to make life a lifelong game. This game is very different from anything we know. It is not about what we can receive, but about what we can discover! By connecting to other people, we discover new worlds, other people’s worlds!
How do we achieve this? Quite simply, we need to focus on others rather than on ourselves. This may sound simple, but if you try it, you will realize how self-absorbed you are.
We are all like that. Even those who feel that they are generous and giving are absorbed in their giving and do not see how much they do it for their own interest, and how they are focused on their own benefit when they give. Giving is fine, but the focus is the point here. Had the focus been on the receiver, the giver would have discovered countless revelations that are hidden from a self-centered eye.
For the game to succeed, you need partners. It is impossible to play the game of giving without people to whom you can give and from whom you can receive. Therefore, there must be a group of people, up to ten or so, who play the game together.
In order to succeed in discovering the other players’ worlds, we need to think good thoughts about them. Otherwise, we will have no incentive to approach them, no desire to discover their world. We can think good thoughts about each other if we do good things for one another. These can be the simplest things, but they must make us feel good about each other. Positive thoughts about each other bring us closer, and closeness opens our minds and hearts to others, so we can see the world through their eyes.
As with any game, the more we practice, the better we get, and the harder, yet more rewarding the game becomes. But unlike any other game, as we improve in it, we will find that our entire perspective on life changes and expands, and we become wiser and more competent.
The game of life, unlike any other game, reveals to us the secrets of life, the secrets of reality, because when you can look at something from all angles, nothing remains hidden from you.

textDisplay: Maybe not, but as someone that was in a relaisionship with a woman being treated for breast cancer, I can tell you that it has an extremely major affect on a womans sence of self.  I was the person that explained to her that being bald isn't the end of life (having been bald and shaving my head each day since I was 35) but I knew how much pain and adjustment it imposed on her life. She by the way made a full recovery and we are no longer together but are still friends. I thought the "WOKE" society was dying, while I don't advocate violence in any form, the slap was not that violent and to joke about someone while ignorant of the facts, is probably more violent in it's affect. (p.s. I don't really care if you agree or not, but to draw attention to something unusual without knowing it's cause is just as violent, IGNORANCE is not comedy)

textDisplay: Not that Will Smith was in the right, because obviously he overreacted. But the difference between Ricky Gervais and Chris Rock is that Ricky's humour is about the stupid shit people DO, while Chris' is more about making fun of what people ARE. It feels much less playful to make fun of things people have no real control over, like baldness, than it is to make fun of people's behaviour and choices.
textOriginal: Not that Will Smith was in the right, because obviously he overreacted. But the difference between Ricky Gervais and Chris Rock is that Ricky's humour is about the stupid shit people DO, while Chris' is more about making fun of what people ARE. textDisplay: It is so important that award shows have comedians hosting and that they make fun of them. Think of the extravagance and superfluousness of an event like this. It would really hard not to get caught up in it and get an overinflated sense of self if you regularly attend events like this. If you get precious (its sort of ok to be a bit bothered if the joke was really harsh, but you can't be precious about it) about a well-constructed joke made at your expense, then it means you have allowed yourself to believe in the pedestal under your feet. Sometimes, in amongst all the wealth, success, admiration and job fulfillment, it is good to be reminded that you still shit like everyone else so that you don't lose your connection to regular people.

Third, people may or may not get angry when other people INSULT them and their family, It doesn't matter if the person laugh or not. When his family gets angry, he can get angry afterwards. Even before that he was laughing. People are sensitive to their families' feeling even when they previously laughing at the joke in the first place.

Forth, this is not the first time his family was INSULTED by the same comedian on stage.

And you will say "it should not result to violence" in this case. Like I say on my second point, I really don't know whether a slap is consider a justice or not if people insult your family, not in terms of law but in terms of humanity. You should STOP this TERRIBLE CULTURE and says to all comedians they SHOULDN'T make jokes by INSULTING the people  and their families again. PERIOD.
